Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
cutRectilinearInst(25.10)                            cutRectilinearInst(25.10)

Name
       cutRectilinearInst  -  Cuts partition or black box boundaries to recti-
       linear instances that fit blocks in a given die, without modifying  the
       existing block area

Syntax
        cutRectilinearInst

       [-help]

       -inst <instName>

       {{-refInst <instName> [-spacingX <xvalue>] [-spacingY <yvalue>]} |

       {-cutBox  {<x1  y1  x2  y2>}}  |  {-corner <cornerValue> [-x <value> -y
       <value>]}}

       [-pushOut <sideEdgeName>]

       Cuts partition or black box boundaries to  rectilinear  instances  that
       fit  blocks  in a given die, without modifying the existing block area.
       The command performs the rectilinear cut based on the following  crite-
       ria that you specify:

              * The name of a hierarchical instance.

              * The name of a referenced instance.

              * The name of corner where the cut is to be defined.

              * The  x and y offset values, in microns, from a specific corner
                or an overlapping area.

              * The name of a side or edge that is to be pushed out, to  main-
                tain the existing block area.

       You can use the command at any point in the design flow

Parameters
       -corner <cornerValue>
              Specifies  the  name of a corner from where the cut is to be de-
              fined. This can be lx, ly, ux, uy coordinates, or edge number in
              case of a rectilinear corner. Edge numbers  are  counted  clock-
              wise from the lower left corner starting with 0.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -cutBox
              Specifies the rectilinear box that is to be cut.

              * <x1>: Specifies the lower left x coordinate of the cut area.

              * <y1>: Specifies the lower left y coordinate of the cut area.

              * x2: Specifies the upper right x coordinate of the cut area.

              * y2: Specifies the upper right y coordinate of the cut area.

              Data_type: box, optional

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each cutRectilinearInst  parameter.  For  a  de-
              tailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use
              the man command:

              man cutRectilinearInst

       -inst <instName>
              Specifies  the name of a hierarchical instance. The instance can
              be a module, an uncommitted partition or a black box.

              Data_type: (inst|hinst|group)+, required

       -pushOut <sideEdgeName>
              Specifies the x offset value, in microns, from a specified  cor-
              ner.  Corner  numbers are counted clock-wise from the lower left
              corner starting with 0. This can be:

              * top

              * bottom

              * left

              * right

              * rectilinear edge number

              Note: If you do not specify a side  or  edge,  the  cutRectilin-
              earInst  command will not maintain the existing area and all the
              sides or edges are modified by default.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -refInst <instName>
              Specifies the name of a reference instance. The instance can  be
              a module, an uncommitted partition, a black box or a hard macro.

              Data_type: (inst|hinst|group)+, required

       -spacingX <xValue>
              Specifies  the  x  offset  value, in microns, of the overlapping
              area between the specified block and the reference object.

              Default: 0

              Data_type: float, optional

       -spacingY <yValue>
              Specifies the y offset value, in  microns,  of  the  overlapping
              area between the specified block and the reference object.

              Default: 0

              Data_type: float, optional

       -x <xValue>
              Specifies  the x offset value, in microns, from a specified cor-
              ner. Corner numbers are counted clock-wise from the  lower  left
              corner starting with 0.

              Data_type: float, optional

       -y <yValue>
              Specifies  the y offset value, in microns, from a specified cor-
              ner.

              Data_type: float, optional

Example
              *

                The following command cuts away the area of proc0/rf0/u0 which
                overlaps proc0/cmem0/itags0/u0/id0, plus an additional 30um in
                the X-direction and 15um in the Y-direction resulting  in  the
                shape below:

                cutRectilinearInst       -inst      proc0/rf0/u0      -refInst
                proc0/cmem0/itags0/u0/id0 -spacingX 30 -spacingY 15

              *

                The following command cuts away the intersection of the module
                and cut box resulting in the shape below:

                cutRectilinearInst -inst proc0/rf0/u0 -cutBox 430 320 670 560

              *

                The following command ccuts the module at corner number 2. The
                cut is 100um in the X-direction and 200um in the Y-direction:

                cutRectilinearInst -inst proc0/rf0/u0 -corner 2 -x 100 -y 200

              *

                The command following cuts the module at corner number 2.  The
                cut  is 100um in the X-direction and 200um in the Y-direction.
                The area is maintained by pushing out the  left  edge  (notice
                utilization of 50% is maintained):

                cutRectilinearInst  -inst proc0/rf0/u0 -corner 2 -x 100 -y 200
                -pushOut left

